{
  "text": "The Affordable Care Act (ACA), introduced in 2010, addressed provisions for healthcare coverage denial due to pre-existing conditions, provided tax-credits and subsidies to purchase health insurance and access to free preventive care, and expanded insurance coverage to include non-disabled single childless adults [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . As part of the ACA provision, childless adults could be Medicaid eligible at or below 133% federal poverty level (FPL) [CITATION_4] . A total of 30 US states including the District of Columbia had expanded Medicaid as part of the ACA by December 31, 2015, however in March 2010, six states and jurisdictions-California, Connecticut, the District of Columbia, Minnesota, New Jersey, and Washington-enacted Medicaid expansion among low-income groups due to the provisions in the ACA [CITATION_5] .",
